			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2022</a> paper:</span><br><i>Selective Traceability for Rule-Based Model-to-Model Transformations</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/QuratUlAinAli.html">Qurat Ul Ain Ali</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/KonstantinosBarmpis.html">Konstantinos Barmpis</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3567512.3567521">10.1145/3567512.3567521</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagM">T5G: Traceability</span></a><ul><li> The central topic is selective traceability for model-to-model transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It targets rule-based model transformation languages and their execution behavior.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Trace models act as mappings between source and target models in horizontal transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Selective traceability is motivated by scalability and performance of transformations.
</li></ul></li></ul>
